For reference, the highest peak in Great Smoky Mountains National Park has been referred to as “Clingmans Dome” since the park’s inception in 1934. Clingmans is a Cherokee word meaning "to wrap around". For years, there have been calls for the name to be changed to a name more reflective of its original meaning. In a vote by the Cherokee Nation, 67% of voters approved a resolution that the highest peak in the park be named “Gilanatlusi” (“The Place Where Fire is Born”), to return the original name to it.
